Partial pooling

Dr R. Morris, School of Psychology, University of Sydney

Sep 12, 2022

library(tidyverse)
library(brms)

We will estimate average trial accuracy using logistic regression, in a random intercept model with a varying intercept for each person.

The example below is shamelessly plagiarised from Solomon Kurz’s adaptation of Richard McElreath’s Statistical Rethinking.


The model

The simulation model of trial accuracy \(i\) for each person \(j = 1...60\):

$$ \[\begin{align} response_i &\sim Binomial(n_i, \ p_i) \\ logit(p_i) &= \alpha_{j[i]} &\text{unique accuracy for each person}\\ \alpha_j &\sim Normal(\bar \alpha, \ \sigma) &\text{adaptive prior for j = 1...60}\\ \\ \bar \alpha &\sim Normal(0, \ 1.5) &\text{prior for average person}\\ \sigma &\sim Exponential(1) &\text{prior for sd of persons}\\ \end{align}\] $$


Assign values to the parameters

Parameters for the population mean (a_bar) and sd (sigma) can be set here. The simulation parameters are shown in the table below, along with a plot of the true values from which the data will be simulated.

a_bar     <- 1.5 # average (log) accuracy for the population
sigma     <- 1.5 # standard deviation of accuracy in the population
n_persons <- 60
n_trial   <- rep(c(5, 10, 25, 35), each = n_persons / 4) %>% as.integer() # trials per person

set.seed(5005)
a_person  <- rnorm(n = n_persons, mean = a_bar, sd = sigma) # accuracy per person

dsim <- tibble(
  person = 1:n_persons,
  block_size = n_trial,
  true_alpha = a_person) %>%
  mutate(
    true_p = inv_logit_scaled(true_alpha))


Simulate correct responses

Each person has \(n_i\) potential correct responses, and so the probablity of a correct response for each person is \(p_i\). The probability \(p_i\) implied by the model definition is:

\[ p_i = \frac{exp(\alpha_i)}{1 + exp(\alpha_i)} \]

A binomial draw from the true parameters gives us the observed (simulated) number of correct trials for each person.

dsim <- dsim %>%
  mutate(correct = rbinom(n = n(), 
                       prob = true_p, 
                       size = block_size))


No pooling estimates

Obtaining the unpooled estimates in this context is simply the calculated probability of a correct response for each person:

dsim <- dsim %>%
  mutate(p_nopool = correct / block_size)


The no_pool estimates are the same as those obtained from a glm, e.g.:

dsim %>%
   mutate(incorrect = block_size - correct) %>%
   glm(cbind(correct, incorrect) ~ 0 + factor(person),
       family = "binomial",
       data = .) %>%
   broom::tidy() %>%
   mutate(p_nopool = inv_logit_scaled(estimate))


Partial pooling estimates

Partially-pooled estimates can be obtained from brms or lme4.

The syntax of this aggregated binomial model will be slightly different in each case. brms uses trials() notation on the LHS to indicate the denominator for each (aggregated) count of correct responses.

brms.fit <- brm(data = dsim, 
                family = binomial,
                correct | trials(block_size) ~ 1 + (1 | person),
                prior = c(prior(normal(0, 1.5), class = Intercept),
                          prior(exponential(1), class = sd)),
                iter = 2000, warmup = 1000, chains = 4, cores = 4,
                seed = 1,
                file = "brms_fit.rds")

The syntax for lme4::glmer() is the standard for aggregated models, and shown below:

library(lme4)
glmer.fit <- glmer(data = dsim, 
                   family = "binomial",
                   formula = cbind(correct, block_size - correct) ~ 1 + (1 | person)
                   # formula = correct / block_size ~ 1 + (1 | person),
                   # weights = block_size
)

After fitting, we extract the partially-pooled or shrunken estimates for each person known as “conditional effects”. The conditional effects are simply the random + fixed effects.

# conditional effects for each person
p_partpool <- coef(brms.fit)$person[, , ] %>% 
  data.frame() %>%
  transmute(
    est.brms = inv_logit_scaled(Estimate)      # brms conditional effects
    ) %>%
  bind_cols(
    coef(glmer.fit)$person[, , ] %>% 
      data.frame() %>%
      rename(Estimate = 1) %>%
      transmute(
        est.glmer = inv_logit_scaled(Estimate) # lme4 conditional effects
        )
    )

# fixed effect (population)
p_fixed <- inv_logit_scaled(fixef(brms.fit)[1,1])

The conditional effects are shrunk towards the fixed effect. For some reason that is not always the case in this example, and I’m not sure why (see stan forums issue here).

Nevertheless, comparing the same conditional effects from a glmer confirms that the conditional effects for every person are shrunk towards the population fixed effect.

Comparing estimates

Calculating the difference between each estimate and the true accuracy rate for each person (\(\alpha_j\)) can tell us which model is better representing the data generating process. Not surprisingly in a multilevel DGP, a multilevel model produces estimates closer to the true parameters from which the data was simulated.

data_to_plot <- dsim %>%
  bind_cols(p_partpool) %>%
  mutate(nopool_error   = abs(p_nopool  - true_p),
         partpool_error = abs(est.glmer - true_p))
